    <item>
      <title>Next generation configuration mgmt</title>
      <link>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2016/01/18/next-generation-configuration-mgmt/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 18 Jan 2016 00:52:10 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2016/01/18/next-generation-configuration-mgmt/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s no secret to the readers of this blog that I&amp;rsquo;ve been active in the configuration management space for some time. I owe most of my knowledge to what I&amp;rsquo;ve learned while working with &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Puppet_%28software%29&#34;&gt;Puppet&lt;/a&gt; and from other hackers working in and around various other communities.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/11/17/iteration-in-puppet&#34;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve published&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/02/20/automatic-hiera-lookups-in-puppet-3-x&#34;&gt;a number&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2012/11/07/preventing-duplicate-parameter-values-in-puppet-types&#34;&gt;of articles&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/05/14/overriding-attributes-of-collected-exported-resources&#34;&gt;in an&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2012/08/23/how-to-avoid-cluster-race-conditions-or-how-to-implement-a-distributed-lock-manager-in-puppet&#34;&gt;attempt&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2014/07/24/hybrid-management-of-freeipa-types-with-puppet&#34;&gt;to push&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2014/06/06/securely-managing-secrets-for-freeipa-with-puppet&#34;&gt;the field&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2014/06/04/hiera-data-in-modules-and-os-independent-puppet&#34;&gt;forwards&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2014/03/24/introducing-puppet-execagain&#34;&gt;and to&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2012/11/14/setting-timed-events-in-puppet&#34;&gt;share the&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/06/04/collecting-duplicate-resources-in-puppet&#34;&gt;knowledge&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/09/28/finite-state-machines-in-puppet&#34;&gt;that I&amp;rsquo;ve&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2012/11/20/recursion-in-puppet-for-no-particular-reason&#34;&gt;learned&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/11/27/advanced-recursion-and-memoization-in-puppet&#34;&gt;with others&lt;/a&gt;. I&amp;rsquo;ve spent many nights thinking about these problems, but it is not without some chagrin that I realized that the current state-of-the-art in configuration management cannot easily (or elegantly) solve all the problems for which I wish to write solutions.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
